  "texts": [
    "The functor C ∶ P 2 • → bpol • descends (by taking quotient) to a functor C b ∶ P 2 • → bpol •/b, by positing C b (I, X) = ca(I, X) and on a morphism φ ∈ P 2 • ((I, X), (J, Y)), C b (φ) ∶= [φ] b (in view of Proposition 4.1.5, φ ∈ BPOL • (ca(I, X), ca(J, Y)).",
    "The verification of the functor properties of C b and K is easy routine.",
    "is a natural isomorphism: indeed a and C b ○ K (a) ≡ ca ○ κ(a) are BG-isomorphic (Definition 3.2.7), since they have the same base, and their Knit are both equal to κ a, in particular they are B-isomorphic (Definition 4.1.6), hence they are isomorphic in bpol •/b.",
    "We conclude that bpol •/b ≃ P 2 •.",
    "◻ BPOL • and isomorphism with P 2 • -We introduce on the p-sites a partial preorder relation → B as follows: a → B a ′ if and only if Base (a) = Base (a ′) and if there exists a BG-map f ∶ Ground( a) → Ground( a ′), and the associated equivalence relation ∼ B defined by a ∼ B a ′ if and only if a → B a ′ and a ′ → B a."
  ],
